&lt;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/humanities/domains/sociology/domains/work/domains/governance/terms/breach/>
  rdf:type schema:Article ;
  schema:url &lt;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/humanities/domains/sociology/domains/work/domains/governance/terms/breach/> ;
  schema:name "Breach" ;
  schema:description "A Breach is a triple (D, t*, p) — a duty or commitment D, a deadline t* at which compliance is assessed, and a performance p whose gap Gap_{t*}(p) \u003e (p,p) — the performance has not reached H*_{t*} by the deadline. The defining structure: breach is the event of a gap that should have been zero remaining positive at the assessment point. Breach creates immediate Hohfeldian consequences: the breaching party acquires a new duty (to remedy) and the injured party acquires a new right (to remedial acts). The RelationalHistoryFiberShadowClassType of the performance element p at deadline t* gives a four-way classification of breach: FixedFiberType means no breach (complete discharge); SatShadowType means the performance is meaning-recognized but not execution-committed — the act is socially acknowledged but not carried forward in every future extension, a paper-compliance breach; TrShadowType means execution-committed but not meaning-recognized — the act carries forward in every extension but has not been acknowledged by the normative system, a completed-but-unrecognized breach; FreeShadowType means both nuclei are absent — the performance is entirely unsettled, a double breach requiring two nuclear applications to reach H*. The breach quantum is the RelationalHistoryFiberSaturationGap [p, σ_{t*}(p)] for TrShadowType breaches and the RelationalHistoryFiberTransferGap for SatShadowType breaches. For Zeno-approaching performances (p settling toward H* at tower level k), the breach quantum is F_k times the distance between RelationalHyperverseGoldenRatio and the ratio F_{k+1}/F_k, equal to RelationalHyperverseGoldenRatio to the power negative k — the exact Hurwitz residual. Total accumulated breach quantum across all levels converges to the Hurwitz constant rather than zero: the irreducible minimum breach quantum that persists through any finite tower-level approach to discharge." ;
  schema:datePublished "2026-03-20" ;
  schema:dateModified "2026-03-20" ;
  schema:isPartOf &lt;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/humanities/domains/sociology/domains/work/domains/governance/> ;
  schema:about &lt;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/humanities/domains/sociology/domains/work/domains/governance/terms/breach/> ;
